proc isHypervisorPresent(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if this application is running inside of a virtual machine (this is by no means foolproof).

proc hasX87fpu(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use x87 floating-point instructions (includes support for single, double, and 80-bit percision floats as per IEEE 754-1985).

By virtue of SSE2 enforced compliance on AMD64 CPUs, this should always be true on 64-bit x86 processors. It should be noted that support of these instructions is deprecated on 64-bit versions of Windows - see MSDN.

  Source Edit 
proc hasMmx(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use MMX SIMD instructions.

By virtue of SSE2 enforced compliance on AMD64 CPUs, this should always be true on 64-bit x86 processors. It should be noted that support of these instructions is deprecated on 64-bit versions of Windows (see MSDN for more info).

  Source Edit 
proc hasMmxExt(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use "Extended MMX" SIMD instructions.

It should be noted that support of these instructions is deprecated on 64-bit versions of Windows (see MSDN for more info).

  Source Edit 
proc has3DNow(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use 3DNow! SIMD instructions.

It should be noted that support of these instructions is deprecated on 64-bit versions of Windows (see MSDN for more info), and that the 3DNow! instructions (with an exception made for the prefetch instructions, see the hasPrefetch procedure) have been phased out of AMD processors since 2010 (see AMD Developer Central for more info).

  Source Edit 
proc has3DNowEnhanced(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use "Enhanced 3DNow!" SIMD instructions.

It should be noted that support of these instructions is deprecated on 64-bit versions of Windows (see MSDN for more info), and that the 3DNow! instructions (with an exception made for the prefetch instructions, see the hasPrefetch procedure) have been phased out of AMD processors since 2010 (see AMD Developer Central for more info).

  Source Edit 
proc hasPrefetch(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use the PREFETCH and PREFETCHW instructions. These instructions originally included as part of 3DNow!, but potentially indepdendent from the rest of it due to changes in contemporary AMD processors (see above).

  Source Edit 
proc hasSse(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use the SSE (Streaming SIMD Extensions) 1.0 instructions, which introduced 128-bit SIMD on x86 machines.

By virtue of SSE2 enforced compliance on AMD64 CPUs, this should always be true on 64-bit x86 processors.

  Source Edit

proc hasAvx(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware can use AVX (Advanced Vector Extensions) 1.0 instructions, which introduced 256-bit SIMD on x86 machines along with addded reencoded versions of prior 128-bit SSE instructions into the more code-dense and non-backward compatible VEX (Vector Extensions) format.

proc hasXop(): bool {...}{.inline, raises: [], tags: [].}

(x86 Only)

Reports true if the hardware has support for the XOP (eXtended Operations) SIMD instructions. These instructions are exclusive to the Bulldozer AMD microarchitecture family (i.e. Bulldozer, Piledriver, Steamroller, and Excavator) and were phased out with the release of the Zen design.
